context: Cuban immigrants in the <a2_0><b7_0>1960s<b7_0/><a2_0/> brought the Cuban sandwich, medianoche, Cuban espresso, and croquetas, all of which have grown in popularity to all Miamians, and have become symbols of the city's varied cuisine. Today, these are part of the local culture, and can be found throughout the city in window cafés, particularly outside of supermarkets and restaurants. Restaurants such as <a0_0><b5_0>Versailles<b5_0/><a0_0/> restaurant in Little Havana is a landmark eatery of Miami. Located on the <a3_0><b8_0>Atlantic<b8_0/><a3_0/> Ocean, and with a long history as a seaport, Miami is also known for its seafood, with many seafood restaurants located along the Miami River, and in and around <a4_0><b9_0>Biscayne Bay<b9_0/><a4_0/>. Miami is also the home of restaurant chains such as Burger King, <a1_0><b6_0>Tony Roma's<b6_0/><a1_0/> and Benihana.
